\section{Step-By-Step Installation}
\label{sec:manualInstall}
	This section contains instructions for installing \cs{RnBeads} manually. The main package, \cs{RnBeads} is dependent on \cs{RnBeadsData}, its companion annotation package. You need to install both packages in order to run \cs{RnBeads} analyses. Additionally, you might need to install \emph{Ghostscript}.
    % \todo{CHANGE THIS SECTION TO USE ONLY ONE OR TWO COMMANDS IN AN R SESSION}

% The easiest way to install \cs{RnBeads} is via Bioconductor.
%
Alternative ways to install depending on your operating system are also described in this section. As a prerequisite, you should have R already installed\footnote{You can obtain R and instructions on how to install it from \href{http://www.r-project.org/}{http://www.r-project.org/}}.

\subsection{Manually from the \cs{RnBeads} website}
	First, download both packages for your operating system from the \cs{RnBeads} website\footnote{\href{http://rnbeads.mpi-inf.mpg.de/}{http://rnbeads.mpi-inf.mpg.de/}}. As a prerequisite for installing \cs{RnBeads}, we need to install additional CRAN and Bioconductor packages that \cs{RnBeads} depends on. If you are certain the packages in the following commands are already installed, you can skip this step. Otherwise, start an R session and install them using the following commands:

<<eval=FALSE>>=
install.packages(c("doParallel", "fields", "foreach", "gplots", "matrixStats",
    "mclust", "mgcv", "RPMM", "wordcloud", "XML"))
source("http://bioconductor.org/biocLite.R")
biocLite(c("biomaRt", "GenomicRanges", "GEOquery", "ggbio", "GOstats", "Gviz",
    "IlluminaHumanMethylation450k.db", "IlluminaHumanMethylation450kmanifest",
	"methylumi", "rtracklayer"))
@
	
	Multiple packages will be installed, which might take a while. When this is done you are ready to install the \cs{RnBeadsData} and \cs{RnBeads} packages. Depending on your operating system there are several options to do so. Follow one of the instructions below.

	\paragraph{Windows:} In your \cs{RGui} application:
		\begin{enumerate}
			\item go to \cs{Packages}\ra\cs{Install package(s) from local zip files}
			\item select the downloaded package \cs{RnBeads.hg19\_0.99.1.zip}
			\item repeat the above steps for the package \cs{RnBeads\_0.99.17.zip}
			\item load the package using the following command in the R console:
<<eval=FALSE>>=
library(RnBeads)
@
			\item If you receive an error matching the pattern \cs{Error: package 'XYZ' could not be loaded} or \cs{There is no package called 'XYZ'} then the package XYZ which \cs{RnBeads} depends on has probably not been installed. You can do this manually by
<<eval=FALSE>>=
install.packages("XYZ")
@
			where you replace \cs{XYZ} with the corresponding package name that raised the error. Some packages \cs{RnBeads} depends on are not in CRAN but have to be installed from Bioconductor. Hence, if you receive an error that the package is not available try:
<<eval=FALSE>>=
source("http://bioconductor.org/biocLite.R")
biocLite("XYZ")
@
			\item repeat the previous two steps until you no longer receive an error when using \cs{library(RnBeads)}

		\end{enumerate}

	\paragraph{Unix/Linux/MacOS:} In the command line (or a Terminal window on MacOS) use:

	    \vspace{5mm}
		\cs{R CMD INSTALL RnBeadsData [PATH\_OF\_DOWNLOADED\_DATA\_ARCHIVE]}

		\cs{R CMD INSTALL RnBeads [PATH\_OF\_DOWNLOADED\_MAIN\_ARCHIVE]}
		\vspace{5mm}

	Here, \cs{[PATH\_OF\_DOWNLOADED\_DATA\_ARCHIVE]} and \cs{[PATH\_OF\_DOWNLOADED\_MAIN\_ARCHIVE]} specify the locations where you downloaded the packages to (\cs{RnBeads.hg19\_0.99.1.tar.gz} and \cs{RnBeads\_0.99.17.tar.gz} respectively). Alternatively, within an R session use the following command:
<<eval=FALSE>>=
install.packages("[PATH_OF_DOWNLOADED_DATA_ARCHIVE]", repos=NULL)
install.packages("[PATH_OF_DOWNLOADED_MAIN_ARCHIVE]", repos=NULL)
@

	You might have to install other packages \cs{RnBeads} depends on from Bioconductor or CRAN. Follow the final three steps described in the Windows section to accomplish that.

